Errorbars
on each line of the data file — (x, y, xlow, xhigh, ylow, yhigh).
see filledcurves, historigrams, errorbars

csv files
Syntax:
set datafile separator {whitespace | tab | comma | "chars"}
"csv" is short for "comma-separated values". The term "csv file" is loosely applied to files in which data
fields are delimited by a specific character, not necessarily a comma. To read data from a csv file you must
tell gnuplot what the field-delimiting character is. For instance to read from a file using semicolon as a field
delimiter:
set datafile separator ";"
See set datafile separator (p. 147). This applies only to files used for input. To create a csv file on
output, use the corresponding separator option to set table.



use -persist option with gnuplot to have the plots persist past the main program's end.

gnuplot -persist <<-EOFMarker
	
EOFMarker
pause -1 "Hit any key to continue"


set output {"<filename>"}

for FILE in data*
do
    gnuplot <<- EOF
        set xlabel "Label"
        set ylabel "Label2"
        set title "Graph title"   
        set term png
        set output "${FILE}.png"
        plot "${FILE}" using 1:2:3:4 with errorbars
EOF
done


shell help:
use AWK (see man awk for help) 
grep ";1;" data.csv pour avoir ttes les 1ères étapes de chaque trajet


horizontal : Boxxyerror
input : x y xlow xhigh ylow yhigh
boxes from x to xhigh >> x=0; xhigh=value
           y to yhigh >> y=position of the box on the y axis; yhigh=position + width 


-d1
historigramme horizontal
y: noms conducteurs
x: nb de trajets effectués




-d2
historigramme horizontal
y: noms conducteurs
x: distance totale parcourue
-l
historigramme vertical
x:id de trajet
y: distance
-t
historigramme vertical regroupé  >> set style histogram clustered
x:villes
y1:nb trajets
y2:nb conducteurs
-s
graphique de type courbes min-max-moyenne >> Errorbars (see above)
3 courbes:
min(x)
max(x)
moy(x)
x: id de trajet
y:distance en km

